<section class="bm-section">
  <h2>Understanding Ferritin: Iron Storage and the Oxidative Burden of Excess</h2>

  <p>Ferritin is one of the most clinically valuable markers on a standard blood panel &#8212; and one of the most commonly misinterpreted. Most people who track their health know that low ferritin causes fatigue and anemia. Far fewer understand that high ferritin, even within the broad "normal" reference range, carries its own set of serious risks. Getting ferritin right requires understanding both ends of the spectrum.</p>

  <p>At its core, ferritin is a storage protein. Each ferritin molecule can hold up to 4,500 iron atoms, sequestering them safely inside cells until they are needed for hemoglobin synthesis, enzyme function, and energy production. A small fraction of this intracellular ferritin leaks into the bloodstream, where it can be measured &#8212; giving clinicians a reliable window into total body iron stores. A low serum ferritin reliably indicates depleted iron stores. A high ferritin indicates either iron excess or, critically, an inflammatory response that is elevating ferritin independently of iron status.</p>

  <p>This dual nature &#8212; ferritin as both an iron marker and an inflammatory marker &#8212; is why interpretation requires context. A ferritin of 250 ng/mL in a man with elevated hsCRP and metabolic syndrome means something entirely different from a ferritin of 250 ng/mL in a man with hereditary hemochromatosis and elevated transferrin saturation. The treatment implications are opposite.</p>
</section>

<section class="bm-section">
  <h2>Standard Reference Ranges vs. Longevity-Optimal Ranges</h2>

  <p>Standard laboratory reference ranges for ferritin are extraordinarily wide &#8212; designed to catch frank iron deficiency and overt iron overload disorders, not to optimize health. For men, most labs flag anything between 24 and 336 ng/mL as normal. For women, the range is typically 11 to 307 ng/mL. A man with ferritin of 320 ng/mL is technically in range, yet research suggests this level is associated with meaningfully elevated cardiovascular risk, insulin resistance, and oxidative stress.</p>

