  <p>The epidemiological data supporting a tighter target is substantial. A large prospective study published in <em>BMC Medicine</em> found a U-shaped relationship between ferritin and all-cause mortality &#8212; risk rising at both ends of the distribution, with the nadir in the 50&#8211;100 ng/mL range. <sup><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30185186/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">1</a></sup> Separate analyses have linked ferritin above 200 ng/mL to a 2&#8211;3-fold increase in type 2 diabetes risk, and ferritin above 300 ng/mL in men to significantly elevated cardiovascular event rates &#8212; even after controlling for known cardiovascular risk factors.</p>
</section>

