<section class="bm-section">
  <h2>Why High Ferritin Accelerates Aging: The Iron-Oxidation Connection</h2>

  <p>Iron is essential for life, but free iron is one of the most potent pro-oxidants in biology. This is why the body invests heavily in iron-binding proteins &#8212; transferrin in the blood, ferritin in cells &#8212; to keep iron sequestered and prevent it from participating in uncontrolled oxidative chemistry.</p>

  <p>When iron stores become chronically elevated, the capacity of these binding proteins can be exceeded, leaving a pool of loosely bound or "labile" iron available to catalyze the Fenton reaction &#8212; a chemical process that converts hydrogen peroxide into hydroxyl radicals, among the most reactive and damaging molecules in the body. Hydroxyl radicals attack DNA, oxidize LDL particles (converting them into the form most likely to deposit in artery walls), damage mitochondrial membranes, and promote cellular senescence.</p>

  <p>This mechanism links chronically elevated iron stores to several aging-related conditions:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cardiovascular disease:</strong> Oxidized LDL is a primary driver of atherosclerosis. High ferritin also promotes endothelial dysfunction and arterial stiffness through iron-mediated oxidative stress independent of LDL cholesterol levels.</li>
    <li><strong>Insulin resistance and type 2 diabetes:</strong> Iron accumulates in pancreatic beta cells and liver tissue, impairing insulin secretion and hepatic insulin sensitivity. Population studies consistently find ferritin in the upper quartile of normal associated with 2&#8211;3 times the diabetes risk of ferritin in the lower quartile.</li>
    <li><strong>Liver disease:</strong> Excess iron accumulation in hepatocytes drives oxidative damage, inflammation, and fibrosis &#8212; independent of alcohol consumption. Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease frequently co-occurs with elevated ferritin, and iron overload accelerates the progression from simple steatosis to steatohepatitis.</li>
    <li><strong>Neurodegeneration:</strong> Iron accumulates in the substantia nigra, hippocampus, and cortex with aging. Elevated iron burden is implicated in Parkinson's disease and Alzheimer's disease pathology, and iron chelation has been investigated as a neuroprotective strategy in preclinical models.</li>
    <li><strong>Cancer:</strong> Iron promotes cell proliferation and is preferentially taken up by rapidly dividing cells. High ferritin has been associated with increased colorectal, liver, and breast cancer risk in prospective studies.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>A particularly compelling line of evidence comes from studies of blood donors. Regular blood donation &#8212; which removes iron from the body &#8212; is associated with lower ferritin, reduced oxidative stress markers, and in some studies, lower rates of myocardial infarction and all-cause mortality. This is consistent with a causal role for iron in aging-related disease, not merely correlation.</p>
</section>

<section class="bm-section">
  <h2>The Other End: Why Low Ferritin Matters Before Anemia Develops</h2>

  <p>The conventional view of iron deficiency focuses on anemia &#8212; the point at which hemoglobin drops and red blood cells become small and pale. But iron depletion causes significant functional impairment well before this stage, during the period when iron stores are depleted but hemoglobin is still maintained.</p>

  <p>This is because iron-dependent functions extend far beyond oxygen transport. Iron is a cofactor in the mitochondrial electron transport chain, making it essential for cellular energy production. It is required by ribonucleotide reductase, the enzyme that synthesizes DNA precursors for cell division. It activates thyroid peroxidase, the enzyme that converts inactive T4 to active T3 thyroid hormone &#8212; explaining why iron deficiency frequently causes or worsens hypothyroid symptoms even when TSH looks normal. And it is a structural component of myoglobin in muscle tissue, directly affecting muscle contractility and endurance capacity.</p>

  <p>The practical consequence: a person with ferritin of 18 ng/mL and normal hemoglobin may be experiencing significant fatigue, reduced VO2 max, hair shedding, cold intolerance, brain fog, and restless legs &#8212; and be told by their doctor that their blood work is "fine" because anemia hasn't yet developed. In the longevity medicine context, the target of 50+ ng/mL is chosen specifically to prevent this pre-anemic depletion state.</p>

  <p>Iron deficiency without anemia is especially common in:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Premenopausal women, particularly those with heavy menstrual cycles</li>
    <li>Endurance athletes (especially runners, due to foot-strike hemolysis and increased turnover)</li>
    <li>People following predominantly plant-based diets (non-heme iron from plants is absorbed at roughly 2&#8211;5% vs. 15&#8211;35% for heme iron from meat)</li>
    <li>People with gastrointestinal conditions affecting absorption (celiac disease, IBD, low stomach acid)</li>
    <li>Frequent blood donors who don't adequately replenish iron</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="bm-section">
  <h2>Interpreting a High Ferritin: Inflammation vs. Iron Overload</h2>

  <p>Before acting on an elevated ferritin result, the first question is always: is this iron overload, or is this inflammation driving ferritin up? The distinction matters enormously for treatment.</p>

  <p>The key investigation is <strong>transferrin saturation</strong> &#8212; the percentage of transferrin (the iron transport protein) that is carrying iron. Normal transferrin saturation is 20&#8211;45%. If ferritin is high and transferrin saturation is also high (&gt;45%), true iron overload is likely &#8212; including possible hereditary hemochromatosis, which affects approximately 1 in 200 people of Northern European descent. If ferritin is high but transferrin saturation is normal or low, inflammation is the most probable explanation.</p>

  <p>Pairing ferritin with <a href="/biomarkers/hscrp">hsCRP</a> adds further clarity. Elevated hsCRP alongside elevated ferritin points strongly toward an inflammatory driver. In this scenario, the priority is identifying and addressing the source of inflammation &#8212; metabolic syndrome, excess adiposity, alcohol, occult infection, autoimmune activity &#8212; rather than attempting to lower iron directly.</p>

  <p>If hereditary hemochromatosis is suspected based on high ferritin and high transferrin saturation, genetic testing for HFE gene variants (C282Y and H63D) is the appropriate next step, ordered through a physician.</p>
</section>

<section class="bm-section">
  <h2>How to Test Ferritin</h2>

  <p>Ferritin is a standard blood test available at any clinical laboratory and is often included in comprehensive metabolic panels. Unlike fasting glucose or lipids, ferritin does not require fasting before the draw, though acute illness or recent vaccination can transiently elevate ferritin &#8212; so testing during a period of normal health gives the most representative result.</p>

  <p><strong>For a complete iron status picture, order alongside:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Serum iron</li>
    <li>Transferrin saturation (TIBC or UIBC + serum iron)</li>
    <li><a href="/biomarkers/hscrp">hsCRP</a> &#8212; to contextualise an elevated ferritin result</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Through a longevity testing service like Function Health, ferritin is included alongside a full metabolic, inflammatory, and hormonal panel &#8212; giving the context needed to interpret it correctly. If you specifically need to retest ferritin to track progress, Ulta Lab Tests offers it as a direct-access test for $15&#8211;25 without a doctor's visit.</p>

  <p>Retesting frequency depends on your baseline. If ferritin is in the optimal range, annual retesting as part of a comprehensive panel is sufficient. If actively working to raise low ferritin through dietary and supplementation changes, retest at 90 days to assess response. If addressing high ferritin through blood donation or dietary changes, retest every 60&#8211;90 days until stable.</p>
</section>

